item.title: Forgive my pessimism but it’s hard to see.
item.description: The GOP has been stonewalling the release of these files for the whole year. They don’t care about us. They don’t care about children. And the MAGA base worships the GOP and Trumplestiltskin like it’s going out of style. I’m a police officer in a red state. I watched dozens of my colleagues speak out in favor of this administration. They ignored the 2 dozen women (and likely countless others) that he has raped. They ignored the 34 felony convictions. They ignored his piss-poor leadership during the pandemic. And now that all of our 401Ks have taken a hit they finally think maybe they don’t care about them. “But I think he has a plan” is something I keep hearing from my colleagues, family and friends. It reeks of an abusive relationship. Every time I hear them say the GOP has a plan I keep hearing a DV victim repeating: “But he says he loves me.” I hope this changes hearts and minds about the GOP. I hope releasing these files will show the world that America is making a turn towards the future. And I hope and pray more than anything the this will put an end to this administration and lead to the collapse of the GOP. But my pessimism is getting the better of me and I’m terrified it won’t matter.

item.title: ICE just tried to deport this woman, but there was just one problem — she was Native American.
item.description:
You read that right: Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) — the agency supposedly tasked with deporting undocumented immigrants — just tried to deport an Indigenous woman whose ancestors have been here for thousands of years. Leticia Jacobo, a 24-year-old member of Arizona’s Salt River Pima-Maricopa Indian Community, was born in Phoenix — but that didn’t stop ICE from trying to ship her “back” to a country she doesn’t even belong to.
Let that sink in: the United States government almost deported an Indigenous woman from her own country. It’s time to abolish this corrupt and incompetent agency that can’t even tell the difference between an immigrant and an Indigenous citizen.
